<s docid="AP900130-0010" num="10" wdcount="28"> Exotic Kashmir, a tourist paradise of 
houseboat hotels and Mogul gardens from whose name the English made 
``cashmere,'' has become a war zone of separatism and religious enmity.</s>
<s docid="AP900130-0010" num="11" wdcount="34"> Military jeeps carry senior government 
officials and civil servants around Srinagar in these dangerous days, as 
soldiers and paramilitary troopers try to stop a campaign of violence by Moslem 
separatists in the Kashmir Valley.</s>
<s docid="AP900821-0092" num="33" wdcount="23"> At least 1,034 people have been killed 
in the Kashmir valley since New Delhi cracked down on the secessionist movement 
on Jan. 20.</s>
<s docid="AP900121-0039" num="39" wdcount="13"> Jammu-Kashmir is the only state with a 
Moslem majority in predominantly Hindu India.</s>
<s docid="AP900130-0010" num="44" wdcount="20"> The most powerful group is the Jammu-
Kashmir Liberation Front, but there are several others, including the Allah 
Tigers, Hezb-e-Mujahed Hezb-e-Islami.</s>
<s docid="AP900208-0116" num="34" wdcount="31"> Kashmiri militants had earlier 
campaigned for union with Pakistan, which claims Kashmir because of its 
predominant Moslem population, but now they demand independence and the status 
of a neutral country .</s>
<s docid="AP900130-0010" num="45" wdcount="10"> India claims the fundamentalists get 
money and weapons from Pakistan.</s>
<s docid="AP900130-0010" num="46" wdcount="4"> The Pakistanis deny it.</s>
<s docid="AP900121-0039" num="34" wdcount="11"> Parts of Kashmir region are claimed by 
both India and Pakistan.</s>
<s docid="AP900121-0039" num="35" wdcount="20"> The dispute started when the state was 
partitioned between the two countries when they gained independence from Britain 
in 1947.</s>
<s docid="AP900212-0061" num="24" wdcount="16"> Pakistan and Indian twice have gone to 
war over Kashmir, in 1948 and again in 1965.</s>
<s docid="AP900130-0010" num="33" wdcount="15"> U.N. observers are stationed on the 
truce line and the two sides occasionally trade gunfire.</s>
<s docid="AP900212-0061" num="23" wdcount="11"> A fluid 840-mile cease-fire line 
separates the Indian and Pakistani Kashmirs.</s>
<s docid="AP900524-0130" num="9" wdcount="26"> Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto on 
Thursday accused India of waging ``genocide'' in secession-minded Kashmir and of 
trying to start a war with Pakistan to deflect attention.</s>
<s docid="AP900718-0069" num="9" wdcount="23"> The government today imposed direct 
federal rule in Kashmir, where Indian security forces are battling to put down a 
rebellion by Moslem separatists.</s>
<s docid="AP900718-0069" num="16" wdcount="22"> The announcement of federal rule 
reflected the belief that Jammu-Kashmir state was too unstable to be run by an 
elected local government.</s>
<s docid="AP900718-0069" num="12" wdcount="28"> Relations between Pakistan and India 
worsened in January when Indian soldiers cracked down on Moslem militants in 
Kashmir who are seeking independence from India or union with Pakistan.</s>
<s docid="AP900718-0069" num="11" wdcount="26"> In the Pakistani capital of Islamabad, 
meanwhile, India and Pakistan opened negotiations today aimed at repairing 
relations threatened by the rebellion in the disputed northern region.</s>
<s docid="AP900718-0069" num="21" wdcount="24"> Indian officials maintain that 
